theorem sampleable_type_vector (α : Type) [SampleableType α] : SampleableType (Vector α 0) := by
  refine' {
    selectElem := pure #v[],
    mem_support_selectElem := fun x => by
      -- We need to show that every vector of length 0 is in the support.
      -- The support of `pure #v[]` is `{#v[]}`, and the only vector of length 0 is `#v[]`.
      -- Therefore, any `x : Vector α 0` must be equal to `#v[]`.
      have h : x = #v[] := by
        apply Vector.ext
        intro i hi
        -- Since the vector is of length 0, the index set is empty, and this case cannot be reached.
        exfalso
        simp_all [Vector.length]
      simp_all [h, support_pure]
    ,
    probOutput_selectElem_eq := fun x y => by
      -- The probability of getting any vector of length 0 is 1, as there is only one such vector.
      simp_all [probOutput_pure]
      <;> simp_all [Vector.length]
      <;> aesop
    ,
    probFailure_selectElem := by
      -- There are no failures, as the selection is always `#v[]`.
      simp [probFailure_pure]
  }
``` 

This proof uses the fact that there is exactly one vector of length 0 (the empty vector), so the support is trivial, and all probability is concentrated on this vector. The `probOutput_selectElem_eq` and `probFailure_selectElem` conditions follow directly from the properties of `pure`. The proof avoids any computational steps over an empty index set by using the fact that vectors of length 0 have no elements.
